}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
//	Created by fenix in 2023
//	License Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 3.0 Unported License.
//
//  Inspired by this video by Nils Berglund:
//
//      https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pN-gi_omIVE
//
//  Demonstration of the concept of a pair of parabolic reflectors. These might be a
//  pair of satellite dishes pointed towards each other.
//  
//  Waves are emitted at the focal point of the left reflector, and form a non-dispersing
//  linear wavefront that travels from left to right. The coherence of this beam allows
//  a signal to be transmitted great distances.
//
//  Notice how the higher-energy colors, yellow and especially reds, only appear briefly
//  when first emanating from the left. After bouncing off the reflector (or not), while
//  travelling across the screen, the wave is mostly blue and green. Only after it
//  bounces off the far reflector and the wave converes into the opposite focal point do
//  the yellows and reds appear again. This would allow a detector placed at the right
//  focal point to recieve a signal transmitted from the left focal point.
//
//  The exterior boundaries are supposed to be absorbing, and they do a decent job, but
//  there is still a small reflection. If anyone knows what I have wrong I would be very
//  grateful for advice. Fighting with BOUND_GAMMA and the absorbing walls was the biggest
//  challenge in making this shader, other than making sure it works comparably in multiple
//  resolutions.
//
//  Click the mouse to emit a circular wave. Suggested experiments: You can emit a wave
//  from the right focal point to transmit a coherent wave back to the left. Also, what
//  happens if you emit a wave near, but not on a focal poiint, for example slightly
//  above, below, or to the left or right. Space to reset once it gets too busy.
//
//  If it's going too fast, I noticed you can easily slow it down to x.25 by just setting
//  Buffer A's iChannel0 to Buffer A to defeat the A->B->C->D->A loop.
//
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

void mainImage( out vec4 O, vec2 u )
{
    // get wave height
    O = texelFetch(iChannel0, ivec2(u), 0);
    O = sin(O.x * 500. * vec4(2, 4, 6, 0)); // colorize
    O *= O;

    vec2 R = iResolution.xy, p = (u - .5 * R) / R.y;

    // draw parabolas
    O = mix(O, vec4(1), smoothstep(3. / R.y + .003, .003, abs(map(p) + .003)));

    // draw foci
    O = mix(O, vec4(1), .3 * smoothstep(.01 + 3. / R.y, .01, distance(p, vec2(FOCUS_DIST, 0))));
    O = mix(O, vec4(1), .3 * smoothstep(.01 + 3. / R.y, .01, distance(p, vec2(-FOCUS_DIST, 0))));
}

